      "popups": [
        {
          "position": [35.52, -84.36],
          "text": "## Chota \n In 1776, Indigenous representatives from northern Nations met in the Cherokee town of Chota, which had grown powerful as a “terminus” of Southern trading routes. Sometimes referred to as the “Grand Talk,” these representatives appealed to the Cherokee to form a united front against settler-colonial incursions (Kane, 2018; 19, 43-45)."
        },
        {
          "position": [39.9526, -75.1652],
          "text": "## Philadelphia \n The Second Continental Congress met in Philadelphia in 1775, in response to the battles at Lexington and Concord, sparking the War of Independence. The Congress was responsible for the Declaration of Independence and served as a national government during the subsequent conflict, continuing to sit until 1781."
        }
      ],
